## S19
Hey everyone! We're dropping a very small update early next week but I thought I'd use this chance to talk about our short term roadmap 🗺️ 


## Dtao 🪙

As Dtao is creeping round the corner, we've prepared a dedicated site to help market ourselves, provide cleaner documentation for miners & validators, and have full details about our subnet

We're also hard at work on the miner dashboards to really help lead the way on that transparency - they will be here for the next major version upgrade  🤩 

See the page here: https://tauvision.ai/

## Incentive mechanism - uncapped bandwidth 💪

We've mentioned many times over the last few weeks that we feel 1 UID and well load balanced miners is the future of this subnet. 

We're full steam ahead with the changes, and by early next week I'll provide a short term roadmap for that integration, and the changes that will be needed on the miner side.

We will bring uncapped bandwidth, uncapped models, and uncapped rewards for miners. 

## Research & bittensor unique models 🔥

S19 is backed by Corcel Research Labs - where we aim to push the State of the Art (SOTA) models. You might remember us discussing about s19 curating a dataset of Midjourney v6 Images and fine-tuning with them. Well we have well over 1 million mv6 images, and two separate models fine-tuned on Midjourney; OpenVision & MobiusJourney . They are currently in testing and will be on the subnet very soon! 

We have also fine-tuned our own Llama3 based LLM, and we will continue to push the SOTA research in many different directions over the coming months.

The plan is to release these models as open source, with a non-commercial, bittensor-mining or personal use only license. The only place to access the best will be on Bittensor 😎

Side note: We also would love to build and cross collaborate with lots of other research labs interested in giving Bittensor more moat, please reach out if you'd like to work together!

We will continue to push the SOTA in many directions, and provide access to the best models possible 🚀

## Links:

S19 homepage: https://tauvision.ai
Research labs playground for the new models: https://corcel.io/research/app/image

@namoray @other-miners

I may have found another reason why the incentive mechanism fluctuates for miners. This issue, which I discovered during extensive debugging, is beyond the control of miners and has occurred several times in the past few hours.

The problem seems to be the strict 2-second timeout policy for stream synapses (chat) set in `validator_core.py:478`. While usually sufficient, sometimes the Llama, Mixtral, and Finetune backends take longer to respond in-between chunks. My tests show that the chat backends can freeze for 3-4 seconds in-between chunks before resuming and flushing everything out in one go. This may have something to do with the backend of the chat servers.

I wanted to report it here so other miners can validate it. Is there a miner here that could perhaps monitor this and confirm?

A simple fix would be to increase the timeout to 6-10 seconds to prevent these freezes from causing the validator to shut down the HTTP connection due to the `sock_read` timeout that is set in `validator_core.py:478`.

As an example: it may start totally fine sending the first 50 chunks, but then it freezes for 2+ seconds, and starts to flush out al ot of chunks at the same time, and then finally ending the stream. However, because of the small freeze in-between, the validator decided to close the link because of the strict 2 second `sock_read` timeout that has been set.

It’s impossible to get smooth changes when validators can only check a small subset of queries

In a perfect world, where all miners reply with the right answer. Even though validators are just checking a small subnet of miners, if every miner in that scoring subnet behaves well, it should be pure competition for the speed bonus between them that makes the incentive chart. Pure theoretically speaking, right?

With the current version however, miners in a subnet that is being scored by a validator have a statistical disadvantage, since some miners get an unfair punishment even though they did their best:
- validators just kill the chat connections and give 0 points in some cases even though the miner did everything right (chat freeze bug)
- validators score an image result wrongly and give 0 points even though it was right (comfyui misconfiguration bug)
- maybe some other bugs that wr are not yet aware of.

So theoretically speaking, when the validators score the miners fairly, the incentive distribution should converge to only the speed bonus even though only a small subnet of miners scored. On top of this, with the new version being pushed today, the convergence will be better, because you increase the synthetic query rate. This results in more samples and hence a better convergence in the weight calculation.

If all miners reply with the right answer and in the right timeframe, then theoretically speaking they'd all be the same

Miners do (and always will, no matter the version) get scored only on a subset of their queries. Any imperfections in the scoring mechanism inevitably have a small influence on this yes

More samples does not necessarily mean more scoring - validators are limited by how many checking queries they can run to score all the miners

With the way bittensor vtrust is designed, validators are tied into checking every single miner for output, since they need to reach a consensus for all miners

Thus, actually, we'd much prefer to have like 30 beefy miners than 256 or 1024 less capable miners

you might find my article on this helpful. during our go rewrite I found a lot of fkd sht with the way bittensor implements it's security checks, this being one of them. something I forgot to mention in the article is specifically how problematic pythons implementation of monotonic_ns is for nonce's. per python docs https://docs.python.org/3/library/time.htm#time.monotonic, the reference point of the monotonic clock is completely undefined. if the validators server restarts, their monotonic clock might start at a much earlier nonce, making their future requests to miners fail the nonce check.
https://www.manifold.inc/posts/bittensor-in-go#example-1-nonce-implementation

unfortunatly, it seems OTF misunderstood how much of an issue this is to upgrade, and reverted my PR for it (which requires a breaking change), since upgrading / fixing requires everyone to do so together
the proper nonce impl, as per my article, is to use a unix timestamp + some sort of grace period to protect from restart attacks which i also outline
unfortunately in it's current state replay attacks are fully possible as long as you know how to forcefully restart a miner
